Overview

This experiment demonstrates how to build a RESTful API using Python and Flask.
We create a backend system that allows users to perform CRUD operations (Create, Read, Update, Delete).

The API communicates using HTTP requests and JSON responses, which is the standard for modern web applications.

This experiment builds on client-server communication and introduces how real-world backend systems are designed.

Objectives
Understand how REST APIs work
Learn different HTTP methods (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE)
Build a CRUD-based backend service
Handle JSON data exchange
Implement basic validation and error handling
Introduce data persistence using files
Requirements
Software
Python 3.x installed
Any code editor (VS Code / PyCharm / Notepad++)
Terminal or Command Prompt
Libraries Used
Flask (lightweight web framework)
Built-in libraries:
json
os
Installation
pip install flask
Project Structure
Experiment-2/
│
├── app.py        # Main API server
├── users.json    # Data storage (auto-created)
└── README.md     # Documentation
How to Run
Step 1: Start Server
python app.py

Server runs on:

http://127.0.0.1:5000/
Workflow
Client sends HTTP request (GET/POST/PUT/DELETE)
Flask server receives request
Server processes logic
Data is read/written from JSON file
Server sends JSON response
Client receives output
Internal Working
Key Concepts
1. REST API

REST (Representational State Transfer) uses HTTP methods:

GET     → Read data
POST    → Create data
PUT     → Update data
DELETE  → Delete data
2. Flask Routing

Routes map URLs to functions:

@app.route('/users', methods=['GET'])

Each route handles a specific operation.

3. In-Memory + File Storage
Data is stored in a list (users)
Persisted in users.json
json.dump(users, file)
json.load(file)
4. JSON Communication

Client sends:

{
  "name": "Rithin",
  "age": 21
}

Server responds:

{
  "message": "User created"
}
5. Request Handling
request.json

Used to extract incoming data from client.

6. Response Handling
jsonify(data)

Used to send structured JSON response.

7. Validation
Checks for required fields
Ensures valid data types

Example:

Age must be a positive integer
Name must exist
8. Communication Flow
Client  -------->  Server
        HTTP Request (JSON)

Server  -------->  Client
        JSON Response